-- India's NSE index hits record high on reform hopes
-- By Abhishek Vishnoi
-- Thu Jul 24, 2014 06:17AM EDT
-- None



MUMBAI, July 24 (Reuters) - India's NSE index <.NSEI> rose to a record high for a second straight session on Thursday after cabinet approval for a higher foreign direct investment limit in insurance and a rejig in foreign debt limits reinforced optimism about the government's reform agenda.  [ID:nL4N0PZ1QM] [ID:nL4N0PY3SW]

Gains were also underpinned by higher emerging equities which hovered near 17-month highs after a private survey in China showed surprisingly strong manufacturing data, boosting blue-chips such as HDFC Bank <HDBK.NS>. [MKTS/GLOB] The NSE index provisionally closed 0.45 percent higher after hitting an all-time high of 7,835.65, surpassing the previous record of 7,809.20 hit on Wednesday.